I used to think of Black history as something that happened before me, now I view it as current actions. 

This year I was trusted to direct and film the Black History Month video for @thenorthface and their first ever Black History Month collection. I wanted to make sure to show the real culture and history of Memphis but most importantly to showcase my hood. 

South Memphis made me, I am Black History. 

#lldolph🐬 #neverstopexploring 

📸: @about35miles

It was a honor to be able to direct and film the first Black History Month video for @thenorthface 

To be a minority in this industry everyday we make history. I’m forever indebted to my ancestors who’ve made sacrifices for me to be able to have these opportunities today. 
Much love to my brothers and sister on the athlete team
(@fred_climbs  @adreadedclimber  @marie_louise_ )

I wanted to showcase the shared experiences amongst black athletes and give a perspective that’s more than why you climb. 
I wanted to showcase my cities history instead of spewing rates about crime and violence. 

I want to thank the wonderful mural artists who help add color to a city full of shades of gray: @alivepaint @khara0ke_studio @tuto_gutierrez @fuma999 and @ellapenaart 

Much love to my fellow photographers @thegreenevan , @aoctaviusw and @trevorlately for helping solidify the vision with a solid edit. 

Last but not least much love to DA BRAND and the whole crew who helped bring this collection to life @msdanyalle @styleandace @kellifashion @chief_sanya @bthebess @katydberg @haylestoner_

@blackfarmlandownersmatter organized a protest today at the state capitol in Denver Co. 

Black Colorado farmer terrorized with no help from local police. CW Mallery and his wife of El Paso county Colorado have endured an onslaught of death threats, farm destruction, trespassing, animal deaths, and constant surveillance. 

An injustice anywhere is a threat to freedom everywhere, let’s come together and support the Mallery’s and the passing of the C.A.R.E.N act.

Today is my Granny’s birthday. I want to honor her by creating and pushing forward in spite of. Last year I lost a lot, my truck, and my loved ones. I shut down in 2022 but this year I promise to keep going no matter what. 

Here is the sizzle trailer for my show ‘Outside Ain’t Free’ it’s centering black stories and voices in the outdoors. I have a bunch of stories to tell and I want you all to come with me! 

Coming soon the pilot episode will be arriving on this planet with the documentary following. If anyone wants to support link in bio and please repost and share, much love 👽

Ouray holds a special place in my heart, it’s the first place I was introduced to ice climbing. Photographing the ice festival for TNF changed the trajectory of my storytelling. 

I was able to take my experiences being the first ice climber from my hood back to South Memphis and laid the foundation for what would become black ice. 

For the pilot episode I’m back in Ouray with @conrad_anker as I explore the ice park and share the experience with my friends.

I sat on the side of the road and wondered what the hell was going on. Why was this pickup truck buzzing us, shouting and honking while we trained our cameras towards the sky. The following day, our tiny team walked into a breakfast spot in Montana when every head turned. We could have heard a pin drop for a moment as I once again sat with a perplexed look on my face over a cup of coffee and a burrito. 

Then it hit me. The reason we were being honked at, shouted at and stared down was exactly the reason why we were filming anything at all—because Outside Ain’t Free. When I set off with @malikthamartian and a small group of Memphians and Mid-Southerners to join a 1,600-mile journey from Boseman to the Bluff City, I intended to be a fly on the wall. Instead, I was tossed onto the film crew as we battled wildfire smoke, grizzly bears, oil leaks and the greatest peril of all, racism, in the opening days of a project that showed me so much of my own privilege in the outdoors. 

This week, the hard work Malik and company have put into this project is finally being revealed to the world. Head over to his page to check it out and see for yourself why Outside Ain’t Free.

Nature grounds me. I grew up in chaos, now I search for places of tranquility. 

Here’s me and my spirit animal 🐐

I still remember when I first saw the Milky Way Galaxy with my own eyes, it entranced me. I’ve been trying to find my passion again when it comes to my camera, I want it to be fun again. I want to be excited to try to nail a shot. Im gonna focus on the stars again because they still make me excited.

2023 The North Face Climbing festival in Chicago

It was a honor to host the 2023 @psicocomp in Chicago. I’m grateful for the opportunity to sit alongside @margojain and bring our best commentary to the stream. So many people brought their expertise to bring this event to life! Much love to @delackmediagroup for guiding me through the process and @msdanyalle for taking care of whatever I needed. Thanks for all the laughs and memories 🤎🤎🤎

#neverstopexploring

Faces from the 2023 @psicocomp. 

I wasn’t on assignment but I challenged myself to get as many portraits as possible. Over the years my portraiture has evolved into this very close and intimate shots using depth to tell a story. 

I remember sitting at the desk of a gym watching the Psicobloc competitions and marveled at the athletic performances displayed. To see it with my eyes and to be hosting is a personal full circle moment. 

Some people think I lost my passion but what I’ve found is that my process is changing. I don’t know what I’m morphing into but I know it’ll be beautiful when it’s all said and done. 🤎

I remember when I first met Conrad and he was like “you should come ice climbing!” I was like why the hell would I do that?! It’s funny how when you follow your dreams it takes you places that you never could imagine. 
My self titled film Malik highlights how people can bond through different experiences. Conrad baptized me in fire and I love the man that came out on the other side. 
Thank you @christomurphy and @max.lowe for following my crazy ass around for weeks at a time. Much love to @yeti for trusting the vision. 

Watch Malik with link in bio 

📸: @max.lowe

One of my fondest memories came on a rest day as we attempted Granite peak. The goat we named Sandy was hanging around base camp all day. I asked her would she do a photoshoot with me and she walked off and disappeared. 
Under my breathing muttered “I guess not” then Sandy re-emerged on a rock behind me. I guess she knew perfect angles while I couldn’t see the bigger picture. 
A lot of people use goat to say greatest of all time and personally I never strives for it. I held myself to a certain standard and just tried to be the best artist I could be. I understand that the result may vary from day to day, but as long as I do my best I can be satisfied how everything turns out. 

Watch MALIK with the link in my bio, if you’ve watched it leave a comment below on what you thought about it!

📸: @max.lowe

YETI PRESENTS | MALIK: Watch the film at the link in our bio.

"It's kind of serendipitous that I've lived my life in a way that even when I was at my lowest, I knew that I was somebody, and there was more out there in the world for me. While filming, I was pushed far beyond what I thought were my limits and abilities. During Conrad and I's expedition, I survived storms on the side of the mountain, encountered a grizzly bear (and lived to tell the story), and climbed to higher heights than I could have ever imagined. I am forever grateful for the bonds Conrad and I forged over the years and to be in his circle of influence." - @malikthamartian 

"When Malik and I met in 2018, we realized we were cut from the same cloth -- a cloth that unfortunately included loss. Over the years, Malik and I have become closer and our friendship has grown to include my sons Max, Sam, and Isaac. When Max and Malik dreamed up a film, I was excited to share what our friendship brings and help create a dialogue of understanding and compassion. And that's good thing." - Ambassador @conrad_anker

This is a people post not a political one. 
It’s easy to be divided when you see humans as labels. 
These people aren’t just Palestinians, they are my friends. Solidarity means standing with the ones who experience the same oppression as you. 
They loved Black Ice because it spoke on the harsh conditions and oppression the people of South Memphis face in America. 
Not too many people understand what it’s like to duck bullets everyday or anytime you leave the house you may not come home because someone decides your life ends here. 
My heart is broken for my Palestinian brothers and sisters. 
No one will be free until all of us are free. 
I whole heartedly support a ceasefire and I stand with all oppressed people around the world until I cannot stand anymore. 

#freepalestine
